The five object types you can build in gold.

The exam expects you to pick the right one for each scenario, so memorise both the shape and the "right when".

First, a plain table — Delta you write with batch jobs. It's stored, and it's right when you need full control over how and when it's written.

Second, a view — a logical query evaluated on read. It stores no data. It's right for light wrapping, security barriers, and hiding P-I-I.

Third, a materialized view, or M-V — a precomputed result that's stored and auto-refreshed. It's right when a heavy aggregation is read often by B-I, like customer-360.

Fourth, a streaming table — append-only, fed by a Structured Streaming query, stored. It's right when records arrive continuously, like daily-card-volume.

And fifth, those last two shapes defined declaratively inside a pipeline, which layers on expectations and lineage — right when you want the framework's quality and lineage built in.

Let me draw out the view, because it's the security-barrier tool. A view stores no data — it's a saved select, evaluated on every read. So you hide P-I-I simply by selecting only the safe columns — customer-i-d, city, country — leaving out email, phone, and date-of-birth. Then you grant select on the view, and analysts literally cannot see what the view doesn't expose. There are also temporary views, which are session-scoped, and global temp views, which cross sessions under the global-temp schema.

But here's the trade-off the exam tests. A view recomputes on every single read. So for a heavy aggregation hit by a thousand dashboard refreshes a day, a materialized view wins easily — it serves a precomputed result, whereas a plain view would re-run that aggregation every time someone loads the dashboard.
